Because I don’t owe ANYONE longevity. Not a single soul. My life is mine to live on my terms.

And shit. Maybe someone comes up with an actual cure and this conversation becomes moot because then there’s a way to be rid of it for good. But until then I have made up my mind about this. And I wish the people in my life that love me actually respected that shit.
I just am so tired. My whole life people have been all up in my business about my health and my body. I want for once to be heard and validated. FOR. ONCE.

The fact that people keep blowing up at me for it and invalidating my own thoughts and feelings about my own health and bodily autonomy is tiresome and depressing. You don’t have to like it. But damn can you at least hear me out and respect it?
I just don’t want to be dealing with machines and treatments and meds and whatever else when I could just live my life as fully as possible until I don’t. And again. That’s MY choice.

I’d rather not sit waiting for it to come back or worrying that it will, when I can just live until I don’t. And that’s MY choice. MY decision. It’s not even like I’m saying take me out right when I get a diagnosis.

Am I aware that people pursue treatments and continue to live long lives after? Absolutely. And I celebrate that for them. For me, the overarching feeling of dread and concern that it could come back even if I beat it before is just not it for me.

The long and short of it is I want to live my life on my terms and go knowing I gave it my all until I couldn’t. I don’t want to be beholden to hospitals and doctors and medicines and treatments for however long w/o any guarantee that it will be gone for good

A little known fact about me: if I were to ever get any type of cancer, I don’t want to go thru with treatments. This has long been a wish of mine for many, varied reasons that I am happy to unpack privately with people I know.

I don’t owe anyone longevity, if I don’t want it. Doesn’t matter what the circumstances are

The fact that I still have to assert this at thirty fucking one is frustrating.

CW: death mention, assisted suicide mention

And it certainly should not ever center straight-sized voices.

And as Hoodoo was hidden within Christianity to protect my ancestors, I do use parts of the Bible and petition some Saints for assistance when warranted. But I’m not a practicing Christian anymore. Haven’t been for nearly two years tbh.
Oh also for the people surprised by the trajectory of this thread, just putting it out there that I don’t identify with Christianity anymore. I think some of the tenets of the faith are legit.
And when the romans adopted the religion, they brought some pagan practices with them…including the celebrations we know as Christmas. So for me, this time of year isn’t for the Christians.

I also think separating Christmas from Christianity helps me a lot. I don’t see it as a Christian holiday. Biblically speaking, it never was (Jesus is a spring baby). It originated from pagan holidays around the winter solstice.

All of that is what makes this time of year magical to me. Not the gifts or whatever else. Just being with loved ones and doing cute and cozy things with good food and drink. That’s the “spirit of the season” for me.

Like I’ve always enjoyed the cozy vibes, traditions with loved ones, food, festive drinks, and stuff like that. And within my own community, I’m finding that again. Going to see lights, drinking coquito/hot chocolate, watching cheesy Christmas films, listening to my fave songs

I am really trying to reclaim my love of this season. Like truly. I think the larger, societal focus on capitalism really sucked the joy out of this time of year for me. But I’m rediscovering the magic on a smaller scale, and it’s been great.

Like I don’t even mind the fertility talk. Because even though I don’t wanna get pregnant, I know loads of folks with PCOS that do. And those conversations can and should be had without diet culture or gendered language being centered.

Maybe I need to curate my own space free of the bs I don’t like 🤔. Like some place where folks with PCOS can talk about stuff and get information without being bombarded with gendered language and diet talk.

Like just tell me what supplements will help with insulin resistance without having to eliminate gluten and what stuff will help with the fatigue and hot flashes thx. Also what will help keep my cramps from nearly taking me out. I don’t need the rest of it.

But yeah. It makes being in spaces for folks with pcos so incredibly challenging. Because I want to discuss things like the chronic fatigue, the hot flashes, the painful periods, and other pesky symptoms without having to navigate diet talk, gendered language, etc.

-the never ending talk about how to lose weight with pcos (I like being fat thx)
-the centering of hirsutism as “bad”/something that needs to be fixed or managed (this is more personal to my fluidity & just me being nitpicky bc hairiness is sometimes euphoric for me)

Things about the PCOS community that irritate me, a genderfluid, fat liberated human:

-the excessive use of gendered language, including terms like ‘cyster’ and ‘cysterhood’ 🤮
-the emphasis on eliminating certain foods to regulate symptoms (gluten and dairy 🙄)
